{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584844"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:58:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:58:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14818"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.27,0,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58853"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7509"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44261"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"8091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18569"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58853"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following occurs first at the site of injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vasoconstriction","Primary haemostasis","Secondary haemostasis","Thrombus and antithrombotic events","Quaternary haemostasis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn response to vascular injury, the first physiological response is \u003Cstrong\u003Evasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E. This immediate reaction reduces blood flow to the area, limiting blood loss and allowing the subsequent haemostatic processes to occur more effectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary haemostasis\u003C/strong\u003E follows vasoconstriction and involves the adhesion and aggregation of platelets to form a temporary platelet plug at the site of injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary haemostasis\u003C/strong\u003E involves the activation of the coagulation cascade, resulting in the formation of a stable fibrin clot that reinforces the platelet plug.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombus and antithrombotic events\u003C/strong\u003E occur as the haemostatic process continues, balancing clot formation with mechanisms to prevent excessive clotting and ensure normal blood flow is restored.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuaternary haemostasis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised stage in the haemostatic process and is not applicable in this context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vasoconstriction is the initial response to vascular injury, reducing blood flow to the affected area.","Primary haemostasis involves the formation of a platelet plug at the site of injury.","Secondary haemostasis involves the coagulation cascade, leading to fibrin clot formation."],"references":["Khan M, Bordes SJ, Murray IV, et al. Physiology, Pulmonary Vasoconstriction. [Updated 2023 Apr 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499962/","Miller MA, Zachary JF. Mechanisms and Morphology of Cellular Injury, Adaptation, and Death. Pathologic Basis of Veterinary Disease. 2017:2\u201343.e19. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-323-35775-3.00001-1. Epub 2017 Feb 17. PMCID: PMC7171462.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences.","Antovic, J. P., \u0026 Blomb\u00e4ck, M. (Eds.). (2013). Essential guide to blood coagulation. London: Wiley-Blackwell."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44261"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44261"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-03T01:51:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T19:39:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7509"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58853"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud8